    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Circle of Fifths and the Circle of Fourths are essentially the same circle viewed from different directions. The Circle of Fifths arranges keys in order of increasing sharps (clockwise), while the Circle of Fourths arranges them in order of increasing flats (counter‑clockwise). Both circles contain the same 12 keys; they just start at different points and move in opposite directions.\n\n**How the Circle of Fourths helps with minor keys**\n\n1. **Relative minor keys**  \n   Each major key has a relative minor that starts a minor third (or a major sixth) below it. On the Circle of Fifths, the relative minor is always two positions counter‑clockwise from the major key. For example, the relative minor of C major is A minor (two steps counter‑clockwise), and the relative minor of G major is E minor.\n\n2. **Key signatures**  \n   Because the Circle of Fourths shows keys in order of flats, it makes it easy to see which keys share the same accidental symbols. If you know the key signature of a major key, you can immediately read the key signature of its relative minor by moving two steps counter‑clockwise.\n\n3. **",
